  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I think about a girl constantly. I will never have her and it's unhealthy, how do I stop this?",
  "response": "It's understandable to feel overwhelmed when thoughts about someone become all-consuming, especially if it feels unhealthy. Here are some steps you can take to help manage these feelings:\n\n1. **Acknowledge Your Feelings**: It's important to recognize and accept your emotions rather than trying to suppress them. Acknowledging your feelings is the first step toward working through them.\n\n2. **Create Distance**: If possible, create physical and emotional distance from the person. This might mean unfollowing them on social media, not engaging in conversations about them, or avoiding places where you might encounter them.\n\n3. **Focus on Yourself**: Use this opportunity to focus on self-care and personal growth. Invest time in hobbies, exercise, or learning new skills. This can help distract your mind and boost your self-esteem.\n\n4. **Challenge Your Thoughts**: When you find yourself thinking about the person, try to challenge these thoughts. Remind yourself of the reasons why pursuing these feelings isn't beneficial for you.\n\n5. **Set Boundaries**: Setting healthy boundaries can help prevent you from slipping back into unhealthy thought patterns. Decide what you\u2019re comfortable with and stick to those boundaries.\n\n6. **Social Support**: Surround yourself with supportive friends and family. Engaging with others can provide a fresh perspective and help you feel less isolated.\n\n7. **Practice Mindfulness**: Techniques like meditation and deep breathing can help you become more aware of your thought patterns and gain better control over them.\n\n8. **Seek Professional Help**: If you find it particularly difficult to manage your feelings on your own, speaking to a therapist or counselor can be incredibly beneficial. They can provide strategies tailored to your needs.\n\nRemember, moving on can be a process, and it's okay to take time to heal. Be patient and kind to yourself as you work through these feelings.",
